Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 wines in the dataset with 13 features (X (wine id), fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, quality).

Other observations: The wines are quite correct in terme of quality (score between 0 and 10) with median 6, min 3 and max 8. The median alcohol is 10.20. Most wines have a pH between 3 and 3.5.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features in the data set are quality, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides and alcohol. I’d like to determine which features are best for predicting the quality of a wine.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Fixed acidity, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH and sulphates help me indirectly to find some relation with the quality of the wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created a variable for the ratio of free sulfur dioxide by total sulfur dioxide. With this variable we can understand more the quantity of the free sulfur dioxide in the wine.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I used the limit and binwidth command to set the position where the data are important and binwidth to find some unusual issues.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

The correlation between features are not significent event if I found some correlation between citric acid with fixed acidity (explain 67%), density with fixed acidity (explain 67%) and pH with fixed.acidity (explain -68%). The last one shows that when the fixed acidity go up the pH go down.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

The fixed acidity tends to increase with the density. Inversely, the citric acid tends to decrease with the pH. Moreover, the density increase with residual sugar but no linearly.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The quality of wine tend to be high when the volatile.acidity is less than citric.acid and both of them are around 0.4 g / dm^3. Moreover, this observation can be reinforce with the radio of free sulfur dioxide by total sulfur dioxide is also around 0.4. Another, the quality is high when the chloride tends to 0, the pH is less than 3.25 and the alcohol is high.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The red wine quality of Vinho Verde is quite correct. The most number of wines is around 5, 6 and 7.

Plot Two

## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 41 rows containing non-finite
## values (stat_boxplot).

Description Two

The volatile acidity median curve (orange) and the citric acid median curve (green) are highly symmetric depending of the quality. Also, we saw that the chlorides median tends to 0 depending of the quality. So, we can say to have a high wine quality, we need to have the acidity less than the citric acid and low chlorides.

Plot Three

Description Three

To have a good quality of wine the volatile acidity must be low (less than 0.6) with the pH between 3 to 3.5.

Reflection

The red wine data set contains information on almost 1600 Vinho Verde wines. I started by understanding the individual variables in the data set, and then I explored interesting questions and leads as I continued to make observations on plots. Eventually, I explored the quality of wines across many variables to find some correlation. I was surprised that some variables did not have a strong correlation with quality. But I found some good correlations (when the fixed acidity go up, the pH go down). After that, I continued to interesting these variables versus the quality. But nothing appear about which variable can explain the quality even if we can exlude the alcohol because he do not impact the quality of wines. So I decided to draw a plot with the previous variables to show some information when the quality tends to high. I struggled understanding to find a clearly variables which explain the red wine quality. Maybe it’s due to the quality score (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts) which are subjective because each person have own preferences in term of taste. Also, a data with more observations would be better to make predictions of red wine Vinho Verde quality.
